{
  "texts": [
    "For each word w i in the sentence, we create a masked sentence S -i, where w i is replaced by a [MASK] token:S -i = [w 1,..., w i-1, [MASK], w i+1,..., w n](2)For each masked sentence S -i, the perplexity P P L -i is computed as:P P L -i = exp ⎛ ⎝ - 1 N ⎛ ⎝ j =i log P(w j | S -i) + log max P(W [MASK] | S -i) ⎞ ⎠ ⎞ ⎠(3)where max P(W [MASK] | S -i) represents the probability of the word with the highest probability in the distribution at the masked position and P(w j | S -i) are the probabilities for the unmasked words.",
    "This step is designed to identify the nonsensical concept in the sentence by analyzing how much each word contributes to violating commonsense.",
    "The intuition is that if a particular word is the cause of the sentence's nonsensical nature, its probability in the model's generated probability distribution for that position should be relatively low.",
    "Therefore, when we replace a nonsensical word with the most probable word predicted by the model, the sentence's perplexity should decrease significantly.",
    "In contrast, normal words, which already have high probabilities in their respective positions, will not cause a substantial change in the sentence's overall perplexity when replaced."
  ]
}